	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>koitsu</b> [ Sun Sep 22, 2013 5:14 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Getting a famicom imported to the US?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />For those of us in the US, eBay is usually the most convenient.  However, you should expect to pay generally absurd amounts of money for it -- there's really no avoiding this on eBay unless you find a really good/ethical seller.<br /><br />For a classic/original Famicom, the prices shouldn't be too bad.  You might get gouged a bit on shipping (particularly if it's being shipped from Japan), but there isn't too much you can do about that.<br /><br />For a Famicom AV, the prices will be much higher -- usually a few hundred.  I got lucky and found a seller in the US who was selling his Famicom AV + one game for a reasonable price and bought it immediately.  I told him who I was/etc. and he said he was thrilled to know it was being bought by someone who'd use it and not simply resell it on eBay for an even higher price.<br /><br />The only other option is to use one of the many Japanese auction sites and rely on a... hrm, what are they called... well there's a term for them but I can't remember.  Basically there's an &quot;agent&quot; or &quot;company&quot; that will buy things from Japanese auction sites on your behalf (for a fee) and then send them to you.  Most Japanese people won't ship out-of-country, hence why these &quot;agents&quot; exist.  Again, there's a term for them, I just can't remember what it is right now.  You might get a better price using that method, but sometimes the fees can be expensive; it varies heavily.<br /><br />I tend to avoid sellers on eBay who are selling consoles out of Hong Kong or other countries -- I stick with Japan only.  The reason is that there's a very good chance what you'll get sold is actually a clone unit.  Some of the sellers disclose if it's a real/original or not (and will usually provide photos of the labels/etc. proving such), but others just say &quot;Famicom blah blah&quot; and what you get is a Hong Kong or Singaporean clone.  The likelihood of this happening from a seller who's in Japan is much lower.<br /><br />IMO, best choice (if you ask me) is just to use eBay and be patient/keep an eye on things.  I tend to use Buy-It-Now a lot because I don't like bidding wars and people who outbid with 1-2 seconds to go.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


