	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tokumaru</b> [ Sat Oct 26, 2013 8:15 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Getting a famicom imported to the US?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">darkhog wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Not only it would be cheaper than getting Famicom, but Pegasus and Dendy are actually better than genuine famicom with more resource-heavy games that would cause slowdowns on Famicom.</div><br />Except they output PAL video at 50Hz. The Dendy is in fact better adapted for PAL than the actual PAL NES is, but since most games weren't adjusted for 50Hz they'll feel sluggish even if there are no lag frames, and music notes in NTSC games will play at the wrong frequencies. So no, I don't think these clones are better options than an original Famicom.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Dendy and Pegasus are the only famiclones I'm aware of that doesn't do &quot;NES on a chip&quot; thing and use genuine parts, so yeah.</div><br />Not using a NOAC doesn't necessarily mean genuine parts, which can only be found in consoles made by Nintendo, so Pegasus and Dendy are definitely not genuine. Several older Famiclones (even though I'm using this term, many had 72-pin cartridge slots, or even both kinds of slots) sold here in Brazil such as the Phantom System, the Turbo/Top Game and the Bit System (this one is remarkably similar to the NES) had individual chips for the CPU and PPU as well, and are reportedly much better than NOAC clones, to the point where they even work with the PowerPak. But that doesn't make them any more genuine. AFAIK, these clones use the UMC UA65XX chips, which may or may not be exact replicas of the original Ricoh chips.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


