	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Sun Oct 27, 2013 1:21 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Getting a famicom imported to the US?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">MottZilla wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">But why bother with that when you can easily stick to official systems?</div><br />Several reasons:<br /><ul><li>Several clones have both 60-pin cassette and 72-pin Game Pak slots in one device. The clone that retrousb.com is about to sell has the slots arranged cleverly such that one slot blocks insertion into the other. </li><li>Pretty much all clones output baseband composite video nowadays. Nintendo never mass-produced a 72-pin AV toploader. A lot of DVD recorders and the like don't have an RF input due to the ATSC tuner mandate. I paid extra for my DVD recorder because it had an ATSC tuner. </li><li>Clones may have the DA15 expansion connector, allowing use of an external alphabetic keyboard, or even a built-in alphabetic keyboard. </li><li>I've seen FC Twin clones (not to be confused with Sharp's Twin Famicom) with Super NES controller ports. This should help with NES games using the Super NES Mouse, such as Thwaite. </li><li>If you're a developer, not everybody buying your game will have an official system. How long will the supply of official systems last anyway? </li></ul>

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


